[The global total number of WPV1-associated AFP cases reported since 1 Jan 2019 is now officially at 51, with 41 cases reported from Pakistan and 10 reported from Afghanistan. The positive WPV1 environmental samples found in Iran, while not viewed as a global threat, are a reminder that the WPV1 is travelling outside of Pakistan and Afghanistan, and if it should arrive in an area with pockets of non-vaccinated individuals, the situation will be ripe for having outbreaks of WPV1 out of the 3 identified endemic countries (Afghanistan, Nigeria, and Pakistan).

Perusing the media reports, there are areas around the world vocalizing concern regarding polio as their vaccination coverages have been falling. See "Polio fears as vaccination rates plunge across southeast Queensland [Australia]" (https://thewest.com.au/news/qld/polio-fears-as-vaccination-rates-plunge-across-southeast-queensland-ng-fb4c1b624084806423954fbeec6bdf98) and "Vaccination rates for babies in Surrey 'well below safe levels'" (https://www.eagleradio.co.uk/news/local-news/2912218/vaccination-rates-for-babies-in-surrey-well-below-safe-levels/).

There are now 15 countries (including China, and 16 if one includes Ghana) that have had documentation of poliovirus circulation in the past 12 months either through positive AFP cases or positive environmental samples. See section [3] below for a discussion on the impact and possible outcomes. Please read section [3] below for an interpretation of the impact and ramifications of this.

For a map showing the locations of cases of WPV and cVDPV, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

